title: Our planets satellite is the Moon
subtitle: The Moon is the only natural satellite of the Earth.
content:
The moon is a cold, dry, lifeless ball, practically devoid of atmosphere; the fifth largest natural satellite in the Solar System. Its size in the sky is quite impressive, and, of course, it became the first target in space research. Until now, the Moon is the only celestial body that a human foot has set foot on.

Structure and atmosphere.

This stone ball has an outer layer of calcium-rich and granite-like rocks. This layer extends to a depth of 48 km on the visible side of the moon, up to 74 km on its reverse side. Under this layer there is a stone mantle rich in silicate minerals, which softens with depth. There may be a small iron core in the center. The Moons atmosphere is extremely sparse. In general, it is equivalent to the amount of gas released during the landing of the Apollo spacecraft. The Moons gravity is six times less than on Earth and cannot hold the atmosphere. But it is replenished by the matter of the solar wind.

The surface of the Moon.

About 4 billion years ago, asteroids began to bombard the surface of the young moon, forming craters. Mountains appeared from the collision of individual rocks. Over time, lava flowing out on the surface filled large craters. Geological activity on the moon has long ended, and in the absence of erosion caused by wind and water, the lunar landscape has changed little over the past two billion years. Today, the Moon is a dead world, covered with a blanket of loose stones. Micrometeorites are still bombarding it; the traces of the astronauts will eventually disappear.

The interaction of the Earth with the Moon.

The moon makes one revolution around the Earth in 27.3 days. At the same time, the Earth moves around the Sun. Therefore, it takes 29.5 days for the Moon to take the same position in relation to the Sun in the earths sky and complete its phase cycle. The attraction of the moon acts on the Earth, causing the oceans on both sides of the planet to rise. This is how the tides arise. Tidal forces slow down the rotation of the Earth, and the Moon moves away from the Earth at a rate of 3 cm per year.

Phases of the Moon.

The sun always illuminates one side of the moon and the Earth. The side of the Moon illuminated by the Sun changes as it moves along its orbit. From Earth, however, only one side of the moon is visible. Sometimes it is fully illuminated, sometimes partially illuminated, or not illuminated at all. This creates the illusion of changing the shape of the Moon. Such changes are called phases. The full cycle of phases is 29.5 days. When the Moon is between the Earth and the Sun, its side is turned towards the Earth, not illuminated; a new moon is coming. As the Moon moves in orbit, the illuminated part of it grows until the full moon comes. Then the moon moves back to the new moon.

Flights to the moon.

More than 60 spacecraft have flown to the moon. They mostly took place in the decade between 1959 and 1969. They were the preparatory stage before the landing of a man on the moon. This goal was achieved by the United States in 1969. At the same time, Soviet spacecraft delivered samples of lunar soil to Earth. Two Soviet all-terrain vehicles Lunokhod-1 and Lunokhod-2 were landed on the Moon. They were moving on the lunar surface. Then the flights stopped until the 1990s.
author: Ersulov
